<br>
&quot;And yes, I think there are already enough resources in our world to guarantee basic rights for people: job, health, education. Let capitalism control the rest&quot;<br>
<br>
You are basically saying that after you gut one of the key, fundamental premises of capitalism, let capitalism thrive!  Think about that for a second.  Everyone has a right to a job.  How would that work exactly?  Everyone over a certain age is guaranteed some type of employment?  Who would be providing this employment, the government or private enterprises?  Would employees be able to be fired?  If so, who would have to hire them afterwards?  What kind of jobs would everyone have a right to enjoy?  Would there be a minimum wage necessary to support a full family for every person who seeks a job?  At the end of the day, the Government will have to step in and provide those basic protections, meaning that the taxpayers will be left holding the bag.  That is beginning to sound like socialism.<br>
<br>
The fact is that the American economy is the most dynamic and thriving in the world because it has not followed that path.  The American economy rewards innovation and risk-taking.  <br>
<br>
Caliopae, our education system is not perfect but it is not as bad as you make it out to be.  There is a reason why citizens all over the world seek to study at American universities and work for American companies.  Go to the muslim countries where America is hated the most and you will find that elites often end up sending their children to get educated in America.  If we were open up the borders of every nation tomorrow, you would see a floodgate like nothing ever witnessed of people trying to come live in America.<br>
<br>
