<br>
Here's one point I would like to make, since so many people seem to think the rich pay tons of taxes.  The top 1% of this country owns 40% of the wealth.  They pay no where near 40% of the taxes.  Primarily, this is due to taxation loopholes written into our system, for example donating to one's own foundation and writing it off as charity.<br>
<br>
This is not to say that the Rich are all scheming evil people, nor that they are all out to get us, or something like that.  However, they don't pay a lot of taxes because when you've got enough money, you can pay for a good accountant.<br>
<br>
Call me socialist if you will, though, but it hurts me to know that because so few own so much, so many others must starve.  In a country as rich as  ours, I feel it is an embarasment that we leave starving children, women, and men, unemployed workers and military veterans, single mothers and mentally challenged folks, on the streets.  I personally believe that food, shelter, water, and health care should be basic human rights (though they're not in the constitution), and should be handled for everyone.  You work, you gain the luxuries of life, though not everyone can do that.  But the punishment for being unable to get a job should not be homelessness, not in a country as rich as ours.<br>
<br>
However, to make sure that doesn't happen the government needs money, and taking the largest chunk of that money from the middle class hurts the economy, because that's the people who do the spending the most.  The poor can't afford it, either.  So it has to come from those who have a lot... and here's a crazy reverse trickle down theory for you: if the rich are being taxed more, they'll have to use more investments to keep themselves in the style they are used to, so they'll invest more and thus improve the economy.  Sounds pretty, probably as logical as trickle down, but it amuses me.  At any rate, money could be then used for those basic human rights I wrote about above.<br>
<br>
